<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1059,1335,1445]" pageId="9" pageNumber="968">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1841" box="[462,559,1335,1356]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Perilypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="970" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[462,559,1335,1356]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="968">Perilypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SPINOLA was revised in 1977 (EKIS 1977). This work included a key to species. The available 
<taxonomicName box="[632,792,1365,1386]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Perilypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="968" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arsus">
<emphasis box="[632,792,1365,1386]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="968">Perilypus arsus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens keys out to 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="968">P. cultratus</emphasis>
EKIS, from which 
<taxonomicName box="[446,608,1394,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Perilypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="968" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arsus">
<emphasis box="[446,608,1394,1416]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="968">Perilypus arsus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens differ by showing significantly narrower phallobasic lobes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1059,1461,1600]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1059,211,438]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="969" pageId="9" pageNumber="968">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 7.0 mm; width 2.0 mm. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,1461,1483]" captionStart="Figs 270-273" captionStartId="95.[151,191,1512,1534]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,224,1495]" captionTargetId="figure@95.[153,1061,196,1495]" captionTargetPageId="95" captionText="Figs 270-273: Habitus; (270) Aphelocerus yoro; (271) Perilypus alpinus; (272) P. apunctus; (273) P. arsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746796" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746796/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="968">Fig. 273</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium flavotestaceous; antenna black; pronotum bicolorous, mostly flavotestaceous, collar black; pterothorax black except mesosternum yellow; elytra black, with faintly visible bluish tinge. Head: Interocular depression moderately deep, crescentic; frontal umbo prominent; cranium minutely punctate; antenna moderately serrate, not densely setose, antennomeres gradually increasing in diameter from scape to antennomere 11; eyes finely facetted, eye narrower than frons (EW/FW 28/45). Thorax: Pronotum transverse (
<figureCitation box="[277,375,270,292]" captionStart="Figs 179-193" captionStartId="81.[151,191,1359,1381]" captionTargetBox="[167,1032,201,1342]" captionTargetId="figure@81.[152,1058,201,1346]" captionTargetPageId="81" captionText="Figs 179-193: Pronota; 179) Phonius versus; (180) Perilypus arsus; (181) A. nodus; (182) Pyticara frontegalba; (183) Pelonium implacide; (184) Neorthoplera quintana; (185) Perilypus virgulatus; (186) P. alpinus; (187) Amboakis expandosa; (188) Ampleris jatai; (189) Megaphloeus jasuni; (190) Amboakis bermejo (191) Madoniella delta; (192) Megaphloeus imparilus; (193) Pyticeroides brevitubulus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746768" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746768/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="969">Fig. 180</figureCitation>
), very finely punctate; pronotal arch well defined; subapical depression well defined; side margins of pronotum proper strongly arcuate (PW/PL 100/93); elytra oblong rectangulate, pubescence short and profusely distributed throughout disc; disc punctures small and profusely distributed on disc, epipleural fold plane (EL/EW 305/75). Abdomen: Pygidium transverse 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[734,741,387,409]" pageId="10" pageNumber="969">/</emphasis>
scutiform; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 207-212" captionStartId="84.[151,191,1256,1278]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,199,1242]" captionTargetId="figure@84.[153,1061,199,1242]" captionTargetPageId="84" captionText="Figs 207-212: Aedeagi; (207) Aphelocerus tigra; (208) A. yoro; (209) Perilypus alpinus; (210) P. apunctus; (211) P. arsus; (212) P. izabal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746774" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746774/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="969">Fig. 211</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1058,454,535]" pageId="10" pageNumber="969">
Variation: The 
<typeStatus box="[307,404,455,476]" pageId="10" pageNumber="969">paratypes</typeStatus>
are more melanistic that the 
<typeStatus box="[703,795,454,476]" pageId="10" pageNumber="969">holotype</typeStatus>
. Each elytron may have a yellow line and the pronotal disc may show a centrally located broad black marking. In one 
<typeStatus box="[194,284,513,534]" pageId="10" pageNumber="969">paratype</typeStatus>
, the elytral discal line is only faintly visible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1058,550,601]" pageId="10" pageNumber="969">N a t u r a l H i s t o r y: The available specimens were collected during June, by beating, at altitudes that ranges from 700-1100.</paragraph>
